default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the number of initiatives
default in the area of retaining and advancing women in STEMM academic careers and the fact that 
defaultmost men and women in academia explicitly, and sincerely, profess to hold egalitarian beliefs the effect of unconscious bias on limiting our ability to achieve the de
defaultsired goals cannot be understated.  Recent research in this area has underlined the fact that non-conscious hypotheses about sex differences play a central role in shaping men and women’s professional lives and that these hypotheses are held by both male a
defaultnd female STEMM practitioners. 
defaultThese hypotheses affect 
default&#xa0;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExpectations of men and women
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEvaluation of their work
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEvaluation of their performance
default&#xa0;
defaultThe effect of unconscious bias can be addressed but in order to ensure accurate evaluations, we need not only institutional policies but also increasing numbers in candidate pools, challenging of hypotheses, and accountability.   
defaultDirect training events sh
defaultowing exemplars have been shown to be effective in promoting discussion as to unconscious bias and its effect on evaluation outcomes.
defaultThe effect of unconscious bias may be exacerbated in the near future by the effect of changes in U.K. retirement legislati
defaulton.  If one accepts the evidence base that shows that the men have a disproportionally strong representation in both senior positions within STEMM academics departments and senior university roles then it follows that we are approaching an era where the tu
defaultrnover of individuals in senior positions may be slowed for some time, thus not facilitating more (currently) junior women to move into these roles. 
default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the current demographics that are in place this position will not be easily overturned without the 
defaultimplementation of deliberate government policy/interventions.
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 2: When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?
default&#xa0;
defaultWe
default not in a position to answer this question and in fact believe that even at a national level there is no effective tracking of such movement within any sector of the labour force.  Exit interviews are not routinely taken up by leavers even in circumstances
default where they are offered and as a result HR departments are limited as to the longitudinal data that they can acquire. However it must be assumed that when highly trained women leave academia there is an important loss of human capital from the sector.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn 
defaultsome instances women may transition to an industrial science career but as the data shows that there is also a leaky pipeline within that sector it must be assumed that in many cases the transition is made into careers which their transferable skills may b
defaulte put to good use but where the majority of the high level research and technical skills that they have acquired are not utilised.  
default&#xa0;
defaultRCUK should provide the statistical data on leavers from the post-doctoral positions that they fund as this information is
default required for completion of a final grant report.
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 3: What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?
default&#xa0;defaultWhilst there is a continuing need to provision 
defaulta strong evidence based organisational framework, with a high degree of differentiation and to drill down into data to look at where the critical points on the career ladder occur in each STEMM area, in many a
defaultreas of STEMM this evidence framework exists up to the present time and this analysis has been carried out in some detail over the last decade by the professional bodies associated with the disciplines. 
defaultThis has allowed for some macro analysis and presente
defaultd the opportunity for policy makers/educational practitioners/practitioner activists to learn from the initiatives implemented. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever given that there have been ~3 decades of UK initiatives on and projects designed to recruit and retain girls and women
default into STEMM fields and to facilitate their progress, with relatively little impact, it is important that we now think critically about the range of frameworks and practices and evaluate why such little progress has actually been made.
