defaultOne example of good practice within the 
defaultUoN
default 
default  
defaultthat attempts to address these issues, albeit for a relatively 
defaultsmall cohort of staff, is the '
defaultThe University of Nottingham Anne McLaren Fellowships
default'
default 
defaultprogram. This is 
defaulttargeted at exceptional female scientists and engineers who seek to establish a research career in the UK. The Fellowships provide a recognised first ste
defaultp into an independent research career
default and are 
default funded by the 
defaultUoNs
default Research Board
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultEach fellowship offers:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultOver the last ten years, the Anne McLaren Fellowships for female researchers in STEMM subjects have attracted outstanding e
defaultarly career researchers across a range of disciplines to the University. To date, the programme has provided ~ 50 early career female researchers a strong basis from which to develop their research careers.  It is key to its effectiveness that all componen
defaultts of this fellowship are in place.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition to the establishment of the 
defaultWinSET
default committee we also highlight three other examples of good practice undertaken at 
defaultUoN
default. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultAPPLE is an award-winning positive action programme to help women at junior and senior lecturer level to achieve their career goals and potential offered by Professional Development, 
defaultUoN
default. Analysis of 
defaultUo
defaultN
default promotions and appraisal data highlights that the programme has supported enhancements to job performance. Feedback from women who have attended the 
defaultAPPLE programme shows that many women feel more confident in taking on more responsibility or a new role.
default Many previous delegates say that a significant benefit of the programme has been to expand their network of people within the University and this has allowed them to work more effectively (for example, in collaborating and winning research funding).
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultWAND provides a progression from the APPLE programme. It is available to those in 
defaultin
default academic role at the University, at a senior lecturer level and early in the professorial career. Participants are enabled to: 
default&#xa0;
defaultIdentify / clarify their career goals  
defaultId
defaultentify their strengths and development opportunities  
defaultDevelop strategies and enhance skills / knowledge to support their career choice(s)  
defaultReceive one-to-one career support / advice from a mentor  
defaultExtend their personal networks and build coalitions with
default colleagues
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Women’s Network provides an informal forum for debate and raising awareness, ensuring that women are not unfairly disadvantaged in order to promote diversity and equal opportunities both within and
default outside the institution. The Network acts as a mechanism for communication with the University including raising issues of University practice and procedure. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThese initiatives are not restricted to the STEMM disciplines. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAthena SWAN and JUNO
defaultAt a nati
defaultonal level the Athena SWAN scheme and schemes such as the JUNO project of the Institute of Physics are examples of good practice where recognition is made of HE institutions that have put in place a number of actions and policies in order to work for gende
defaultr proportionality within STEMM.  There has been considerably ‘buy in’ by the HE community for these schemes and their importance has been underlined by the support given to them by such preeminent individuals as the Chief Medical Officer Professor Dame Sal
defaultly Davies. Her statement that any NHS/University partnerships applying for NIHR funding in 2015 where the academic partner has not achieved at least the Silver Award of the Athena SWAN Charter for Women in Science should not expect to be shortlisted, was a
default clear signpost of the commitment that all funding bodies should be expected to demonstrate to promoting gender proportionality in STEMM.
default    
defaultWe wish to emphasise the impact that adoption of the Athena SWAN charter has had in HE institutions, and to recogndefaultise the support that it has given to those wishing to adopt and maintain good practice in regard to staff and students within the STEMM disciplines.default&#xa0;defaultQuestion 4: What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEMM c
defaultareers? 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe need for holistic cultural change in STEMM higher education, covering both staff and students, will mean that issues will have to be addressed at a number of different levels but importantly by partnerships between educators and Government. In addition
default there are issues that can only be initiated and tackled by government via funding bodies and via legislation. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Research Excellence Framework (REF).
default&#xa0;
defaultThe REF
default&#xa0;
defaultEquality and Diversity 
defaultAdvisory Panel (EDAP)
default 
defaultprovides advice to the funding bodies, the REF team and the REF panels on the implementation of equality measures, reviewing institutions' codes of practice on the selection of staff and producing a 
defaultreport of good practic
defaulte
default found in the codes. Over the course of the REF period this has resulted in some changes in the criteria and implementation of equality measures.  There is however a wid
defaultespread feeling within the community that these measures were only brought in after considerable voicing of disquiet from bodies and individuals concerned to promote gender proportionality within academia and that outside certain universities there remains
default a large degree of second guessing as to what the rules mean and the level to which individuals can be hidden in order to maximize financial benefit.  
default&#xa0;
defaultGrant Evaluations (Research Councils UK).
default&#xa0;
defaultIf we follow on from the findings of the REF EDAP on impleme
defaultntation of equality measures when assessing research excellence it is important that in the allocation of funding for research a similar implementation of equality measures takes place.  It is also strongly suggested that RCUK are required to publish gende
defaultr disaggregated data on submissions and success rates.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Supply Side.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne important component of addressing the retention of women in STEMM is on the supply side.  Research has shown that for any component of a labour force that can be identified by a 
defaultspecific characteristic the presence within a unit needs to rise to &gt; 20% before the evaluation of their contribution becomes automatically fair and reasonable.  In some STEMM disciplines the undergraduate intake to the discipline is dangerously close to t
defaulthat figure, and in many instances it declines very quickly to a far smaller percentage.  Therefore there is the issue of the STEMM pipeline in schools which requires Government initiatives and funding.
default&#xa0;
defaultFinally a last statement to emphasise that we welcomedefault this inquiry and hope that its findings and conclusions will lead to the implementation of policy in school, universities and government to promote gender proportionality in STEMM subjects.default&#xa0;defaultWe also hope that all defaultpolitical defaultparties are taking steps to encourage potential candidates with science backgrounds default(defaultof both gendersdefault)default to put themselves forward as candidates in the next election. Perhaps the appointment of the first female Chief Scientific Advisor to the Government woulddefault point the way forward?default&#xa0;defaultReferences.
